[[File:2009 Aston Villa.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Guzan (dressed in yellow) lines up  with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] team-mates prior to a [[UEFA Europa League]] match away at [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Vienna]] in August 2009.]]
'''Bradley Edwin "Brad" Guzan''' {{IPAc-en|<U+02C8>|g|u<U+02D0>|z|<U+0259>n}} (born September 9, 1984) is an American [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for English [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

==Club career==

===Early career===
Born in [[Evergreen Park, Illinois|Evergreen Park]], [[Illinois]], Guzan, who is of [[Polish-American]] ancestry, played his youth soccer at the Chicago Magic Soccer Club, and for the varsity soccer team at [[Providence Catholic High School]] in Illinois, from which he graduated in 2003. He went on to play two seasons in [[college soccer|NCAA]] competition as a member of the [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's soccer]] team, where he was a second-team [[All-American]] in his sophomore season.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Chivas USA picks GK Brad Guzan <U+2013> MLS SuperDraft 2005 | url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3117115 | publisher=OurSportsCentral | date=January 5, 2005}}</ref>

=== Chivas USA ===
After spending two years with the [[Chicago Fire Reserves]] in the [[USL Premier Development League]] he chose to forgo the rest of his college years, signing a [[Generation Adidas]] contract with [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS). [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]] drafted Guzan with the second overall pick of the [[2005 MLS SuperDraft]].

Guzan has played for the Under-18 [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]]. He got his first cap for the senior national team on February 19, 2006, against [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]]. On November 7, 2007, Guzan was named [[MLS Goalkeeper of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite news| title=Chivas USA's Guzan wins top goalkeeper | url=http://msn.foxsports.com/other/story/7395318 | accessdate=November 7, 2007}}</ref>

===Aston Villa===
July 11, 2008, [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] agreed a transfer fee in the region of <U+00A3>600,000, or $1 million, with MLS and Chivas USA to sign Guzan, significantly less than the <U+00A3>2 million agreed to in Aston Villa's failed move for the keeper in January 2008. This was because Guzan would have been out of his contract at the end of the [[2008 Major League Soccer season|2008 season]] in November, allowing him to sign for Aston Villa during the January transfer window on a free transfer.

On August 1, 2008, Guzan was granted a [[Work permit (United Kingdom)|work permit]] by the [[Home Office]], allowing him to complete his move to Aston Villa.<ref name=villa-move-final>{{Cite news| last=Michaels | first=Steve | title=Villa Given Guzan Work Permit | url=http://www.goal.com/en/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=800793 | publisher=[[Goal.com]] | date=August 1, 2008 | accessdate=August 1, 2008}}</ref> He was due to be officially introduced by Aston Villa after competing for the United States at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]]. Guzan was the second American goalkeeper called Brad to be signed during the summer by Villa, following the capture of Premier League veteran [[Brad Friedel]].

Guzan made his Villa debut in September 2008, in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], at home to [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].

He made his European debut in the [[UEFA Cup]] game away at [[Slavia Prague]] on November 6, 2008. The match finished 1<U+2013>0 to [[Aston Villa]] with Guzan making several saves to keep a clean sheet. His performance led to his manager, [[Martin O'Neill]], describing him as a "class goalkeeper in the making." He also started in Villa's first leg against CSKA Moscow in round 32 of the UEFA Cup at Villa Park on February 18, 2009, and came on as a substitute against Liverpool after [[Brad Friedel]]'s red card.

Guzan played in every game that Villa won during their success in the [[2009 Peace Cup]], against [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]], [[FC Porto|Porto]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. He helped Villa overcome the Italians in the [[2009 Peace Cup#Final|final]], notably in the penalty shootout where he saved the attempts of [[Vincenzo Iaquinta]] and [[Alessandro Del Piero]].<ref>http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10265~1741264,00.html</ref> The only game that Villa did not win (in the [[2009 Peace Cup#Group C|group stages]] against [[M<U+00E1>laga CF|M<U+00E1>laga]]) was the one in which Guzan did not feature.
Despite having a successful pre-season period, Guzan was dropped from the first team in favour of compatriot and Premier League veteran [[Brad Friedel]] for Villa's opening game of the 2009<U+2013>10 season, against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].

On October 27, 2009, Guzan saved four penalties in one match, one in normal time and three more in a penalty shoot-out win over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] at the [[Stadium of Light]] in the last 16 of the League Cup. Despite these heroics, [[Brad Friedel]] replaced him in goal for the final against Manchester United.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8531179.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | title=Aston Villa 1<U+2013>2 Man Utd | date=February 28, 2010 | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | first=Phil | last=McNulty}}</ref>

====Hull City (loan)====
[[File:Brad Guzan Hull City v. Queens Park Rangers 29-01-11 1.png|thumb|200px|Guzan playing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in 2011]]
On December 31, 2010 Guzan was loaned to [[Football League Championship]] side [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on a one-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11095_6626796,00.html | work=[[Sky Sports]] | title=Tigers land Guzan | date=December 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1343107/Aston-Villa-loan-Brad-Guzan-Hull.html?ITO=1490 |title=Aston Villa loan Brad Guzan to Hull |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=December 31, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref> He made his debut for Hull on New Year's Day 2011, a 1<U+2013>0 loss to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref name="Hull 0 - 1 Leicester">{{Cite news
